{"id":"astro-ph/0006317","submitter":"Pawan Kumar","authors":"Pawan Kumar (IAS), Alin Panaitescu (Princeton university)","title":"Afterglow Emission from Naked Gamma-Ray Bursts","comments":"5 pages, 2 figures, Submitted to ApJ letter","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1086/312905","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We calculate the {\\it afterglow} emission for Gamma-Ray Bursts (GRBs) going\noff in an extremely low density medium, referred to as {\\it naked bursts}. Our\nresults also apply to the case where the external medium density falls off\nsharply at some distance from the burst. The observed afterglow flux in this\ncase originates at high latitudes, i.e. where the angle between the fluid\nvelocity and the observer line of sight is greater than $\\Gamma^{-1}$. The\nobserved peak frequency of the spectrum for naked bursts decreases with\nobserver time as $t^{-1}$, and the flux at the peak of the spectrum falls off\nas $t^{-2}$. The 2--10 keV $X$-ray flux from a naked burst of average fluence\nshould be observable by the SWIFT satellite for time duration of about $10^3$\nlonger than the burst variability timescale. The high latitude emission\ncontributes to the early $X$-ray afterglow flux for any GRB, not just naked\nbursts, and can be separated from the shocked inter-stellar medium (ISM)\nemission by their different spectral and temporal properties. Measurements of\nthe high latitude emission could be used to map the angular structure of GRB\nproducing shells.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 22 Jun 2000 00:06:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
